comment_data.body: I don't think this is true. We coerce struct values to dicts when used in a Python context. That probably also applies here, so I think you could at least compare structs to dicts. We should make sure to not break that feature (and to give a correct error message here).

comment_data.body:
Doesn't this just mean that both sides are not equal?

We could debate whether a struct `(field1, field2)` equals a struct `(field1, field2, field3)` when `field3` is empty (I guess not), but apart from that special question, when I compare two different data structures in Python, it usually just says "not equal" rather than raising errors.

Long function calls (or lengthy calculations) are not easy to read and follow inside of f-string values. Same below.
```suggestion
            struct_code = self.generate_struct_code(self.operand1_temp, self.operand2_temp, operand1.type, operand2.type, op, code)
            code.putln(f"{result_code} = {struct_code};")
```

allow comparisons between structs and python dicts
